Comment: One of my favorite openings for white, the glorious queens gambit.
standard reply to the queen pawn opening.
white sticks with the normal queens gambit opening
This is unorthodox for black
never a bad idea to trade pawns if you can get rid of the black D pawn and keep your own d and e
black takes back the pawn with the only thing that it can use, the queen
white defends its d pawn which is under attack by blacks c pawn and blacks queen
black brings more firepower and puts more pressure on whites D pawn
white decides to abandon the one-ups-man-ship.  Its never a bad idea to attack the queen.  This proves the theory that the queen should stay home until later in the game.
The queen scampers away to a place which puts some mild pressure on whites king side.  Would have been much better for the queen to go home.
When the queen is away, the white horse goes for a fork.  This is always a danger when the queen is away from home.
Black really had no good options to defend the fork. The king had to move which eliminates any possibility for black to castle.
White sees an opportunity to take a pawn and also gives what is known as a "discovered check".  Black can not take back the pawn because he is in check.
Black moves the king out of check and the game is deteriorating for black
White succeeds in creating a fork after all
Black king moves out of check once again.  The black king is in a very unusual place for this early in the game.
White could have taken its bounty, but instead decides to rub salt into the wound.
It gets worse and worse for black.  The king is having a nice trip around the board.
White could have given another check with the Queen but since it wasn't checkmate then white decides its time to take the bounty.
Black pushes a pawn which does 2 things.  1) It makes it possible for black to threaten the white horse on the next move and 2) it opens up the black bishop 3) threatens the white pawn
